commText: Gujarat Titans are on a roll. Sitting at the top of the points table and having lost just 3 games. They have carried on from last season and just like last year there have been different players putting their hand up in different games. The likes of Noor Ahmad, Joshua Little, Abhinav Manohar, Mohit Sharma, Sai Sudharsan have all won them games and the seniors have also contributed. Hardik has once again been impressive with his captaincy and the ever reliable Rashid Khan is ruling the bowling charts with Mohammad Shami. They look like a well-oiled unit even though it is only two years since this bunch are playing together. It would take a perfect game from the Super Giants to beat this in-form Titans team. Toss and teams coming up..

KL Rahul has been ruled out for the season and Krunal has taken over the captaincy reins. Their last game against CSK was a washout and they replaced Rahul with Manan Vohra, keeping the setup of the team almost similar. They have Quinton de Kock on the bench and can bring him in to partner Kyle Mayers at the top but that will leave them with an all Indian bowling attack as the other two overseas spots - Marcus Stoinis and Nicholas Pooran - are almost undroppable. There's also Mark Wood, who started the season with a bang, but has been overlooked because of the impressive Naveen-ul-Haq. They have some decisions to make and it will be interesting to see what combination they put out.

B0$ The last time these two teams met, Gujarat Titans pulled off a heist or you can also put it as Lucknow Super Giants gifting two points to the defending champions. The equation was 30 off the last 5 overs and the Titans won by 7 runs with Mohit Sharma defending 12 in the last over. Anyway, this is a new day, different venue and a little change in Super Giants' captaincy. They haven't beaten the Titans in the three previous encounters. But with the points table getting very tight, the Super Giants need a win to keep up with the leaders. Hello and welcome to the first game of Super Sunday..

B0$ 
 
Just three points separate the two teams but such has been the nature of the tightly-contested season so far, that they are two spots behind by the time the game gets underway. 
 
At this critical juncture, the focus will be on the visitors and how they approach the rest of the season given the absence of KL Rahul, their regular skipper. It would no doubt prompt an overhaul, indications of which were seen in their rain-curtailed game against CSK. 
 
An overhaul more than halfway into the season is bound to pose a lot of questions particularly if the moves don't click. 
 
It is on this knife's edge that they run into the top-ranked side, that has found the going smooth despite not being at their best especially at home. Having lost three out of their five outings here, there is a certain fallibility to the line-up even after a rare hiccup while failing to chase down a total. Their last outing against Delhi saw them lose while chasing for only the second time in 14 attempts, with their skipper Hardik Pandya taking up the blame for failing to finish the chase despite getting a half-century. 
 
However, a clinical performance in the last game against Rajasthan Royals would've again invigorated their campaign.
